{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17659529","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17659529"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:10:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:10:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20867"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20867","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20867"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.12,0.08,0.76,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13742"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97382"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13742","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13742"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20867"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79997"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11595"},{"type":"tags","id":"12690"},{"type":"tags","id":"12691"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33072"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33073"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97382","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97382"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EOrgan transplantation is an important treatment for end-stage organ failure. The success of transplantation depends on preventing rejection of the donor organ by the recipient\u0027s immune system.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of hyperacute rejection of allografts?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Delayed-type hypersensitivity reaction to graft proteins","Natural killer cell destruction of non-self tissues","T cell-mediated cytotoxicity against graft cells","Preformed antibodies binding to graft endothelial antigens","Gradual fibrosis due to chronic inflammatory response"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Epreformed antibodies binding to graft endothelial antigens\u003C/strong\u003E. Hyperacute rejection occurs immediately after transplantation when the recipient\u0027s preformed antibodies bind to antigens on the graft vascular endothelium. These antibodies may be natural IgM antibodies specific for blood group antigens or antibodies against human leucocyte antigen (HLA) molecules induced by prior exposure to allogeneic cells through blood transfusions, pregnancy, or previous transplantation. This antibody binding activates the complement system, leading to endothelial injury, thrombosis, and rapid ischaemic necrosis of the graft.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ET cell-mediated cytotoxicity against graft cells\u003C/strong\u003E - This is a mechanism of acute cellular rejection, not hyperacute rejection. It involves T lymphocytes recognising and attacking foreign HLA molecules on the graft cells.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDelayed-type hypersensitivity reaction to graft proteins\u003C/strong\u003E - This is a cell-mediated immune response that contributes to acute rejection but is not the mechanism of hyperacute rejection.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENatural killer cell destruction of non-self tissues\u003C/strong\u003E - While natural killer cells may play a role in some aspects of transplant rejection, they are not the primary mediators of hyperacute rejection.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGradual fibrosis due to chronic inflammatory response\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes chronic rejection, which develops over months to years and is characterised by progressive fibrosis and vascular changes in the graft.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHyperacute rejection is now rare in clinical practice because potential recipients are tested for antibodies against prospective donor cells (cross-matching) and donors and recipients are matched for blood type before transplantation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Graft rejection is classified into hyperacute, acute, and chronic patterns based on clinical and pathologic features.","Hyperacute rejection is mediated by preformed antibodies against graft endothelial cell antigens, causing rapid vascular thrombosis.","The major antigenic differences between donor and recipient that trigger rejection are differences in human leucocyte antigen (HLA) alleles.","T lymphocytes recognise graft alloantigens through both direct and indirect pathways of antigen presentation."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 6; pages 234-236."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79997"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20867"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79997","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79997"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-06T13:29:52+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-06T13:32:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13742"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97382"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11595","links":{"sel